**Dealing with Complex Systems**

This course is meant to provide you with the essential tools, theories, and techniques needed to succeed as a game designer at a foundational level. I included game systems design because thinking systemically is paramount for a designer to succeed, in my opinion.

With that in mind, this chapter discusses the basics of game system design so that you are not intimidated by game systems design and its terminology. However, game systems design does not stop here. In fact, systems design is one of the most complex and deeper topics in game design. It’s, in some ways, a never-ending search for new and improved systems and the many forms they can take in each new game released to the market.

When your turn comes to deal with systems design, either in your personal projects or at a company, you’ll notice that most of the systems seem messier and more extensive than the ones discussed here and the ones found in elegantly designed games. The reason is that those systems were already refined by the iterative process natural to game design!

When dealing with these complex, messier systems, it will help you to consider the following:

- **Which other games feature similar systems?** — It’s very likely that you’ll find existing games that use a similar set of systems. What are the differences and similarities between these games and the systems you are proposing?
- **Which real-life system displays similar behaviors?** — Finding inspiration in real-life systems is a tough but very rewarding exercise that can massively improve your game's relatedness with your players. The reason is that players already “know” those systems, even if they don’t think deeply about them. Simulation games are a clear example of real-life systems successfully implemented in video games.
- **Where are the reinforcing loops?** — Remember, reinforcing loops are the main points of interaction with players. Most of the time, players will use (and abuse) reinforcing loops to increase their power, money, etc. Make them attractive and rewarding for players to use!
- **Where are the balancing loops?** — Balancing loops are the main points for you as a designer to create a balanced, fair experience for your players. Find the balancing loops and see how you can use them to create better experiences for players. Is your game catered to more casual or hardcore players? Are you creating a game in a fairly known genre, or are you innovating in a relatively unknown one? All of these and more questions will help you determine which kind of balance you need.
- **Can I create a diagram of this system (or a part of it)?** — Creating a diagram is not only a fun way to spend your evenings (at least it is for me!). Diagrams help you and your team visualize the game system. Sometimes it’s extremely difficult to communicate a system only using words, especially if you’re dealing with conveyor belt systems of resources or basic/advanced components, etc. A diagram is a great way to express the inner workings of a system in a concise, easy-to-digest, and enticing way. You’ll become a better designer by diagramming your systems, and your teammates will have a clearer vision and understanding of the system. It’s a win-win situation, so unless you’re extremely pressed for time, consider making a diagram of the system or a part of it.

